## NixOS swapDevices Configuration Options

Swap on NixOS is set with one of two options swapDevices or zramSwap.enable on /etc/nixos/hardware-configuration.nix. The swap devices and swap files. These must have been initialised using mkswap. Each element should be an attribute set specifying either the path of the swap device or file (device) or the label of the swap device (label, see mkswap -L).

### Key Configuration Options

**Device/Label:**
- `device`: Specifies the path to the swap device or file
- `label`: Alternative to device, uses the swap label (recommended)

**Size Option:**
If this option is set, 'device' is interpreted as the path of a swapfile that will be created automatically with the indicated size (in megabytes) if it doesn't exist. Is it only necessary if you want NixOS to auto-create the swapfile for you.

**Priority Option:**
Specify the priority of the swap device. Priority is a value between 0 and 32767. Higher numbers indicate higher priority. null lets the kernel choose a priority, which will show up as a negative value.

### Example Configurations

**Basic swap file with size:**
```nix
swapDevices = [
  {
    device = "/swapfile";
    size = 2048;  # 2GB in megabytes
  }
];
```

**Swap file with size and priority:**
This will create a 16GB swapfile at /var/lib/swapfile. The size value is specified in megabytes:
```nix
swapDevices = [
  {
    device = "/var/lib/swapfile";
    size = 16384;   # 16GB
    priority = 100; # Higher priority
  }
];
```

**Using existing swap partition:**
```nix
swapDevices = [
  {
    device = "/dev/sdXY";
    priority = 50;
  }
];
```

The `size` option is primarily used when you want NixOS to automatically create a swap file for you. If you already have an existing swap file or partition, you typically don't need to specify the size parameter.

